2.about
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>About Gurukula</title>
</head>
<body style= "background: url(about.ca3.jpg);
                background-size:cover;
                background-repeat: no-repeat;
                ">

    <header>
        <h1>About Gurukula</h1>
    </header>
    
        <h2><p>The Gurukula system was a traditional educational institution in ancient India where students lived with their teacher (Guru) to gain knowledge and skills.
        This system emphasized a deep bond between teacher and student, creating an environment of mutual respect and dedicated learning.</p>
        <h1>about gurukula</h1>
        <br>The Gurukula (or Gurukul) system is an ancient educational practice from India where students (referred to as shishyas) live and study under the guidance of a teacher (guru) in a residential setup.
        It was more than just academic education; it focused on the holistic development of students in knowledge, skills, morals, and spiritual growth.</br>
            
        <h2>Key Aspects of the Gurukula System:</h2>
        <br>Residential Learning: Students lived with the teacher in the same environment, often away from cities, to focus entirely on learning.</br>
         <br>Teacher-Student Bond: The relationship between the guru and shishya was close, akin to a family, where respect, trust, and devotion were paramount.</br>
        <br>Practical and Ethical Education: Alongside academics, students learned practical skills (like farming, trade, or warfare) and values, such as discipline, respect, and self-reliance.</br>
        <br> Life Skills and Spiritual Knowledge: The system also emphasized teaching life skills, philosophical and spiritual insights, and the core values of Hindu philosophy, like Dharma (duty), Karma (action), and Moksha (liberation).</br>
        <br>The gurukula system was eventually replaced by colonial and modern educational systems, yet it remains a model for holistic education and is sometimes revived in modern gurukulas, where traditional knowledge is taught alongside formal education.</br></h2>
            
            
            
            
            
            
         </p>
    
</body>
</html>



